Lack of diversity is a known problem in Computer Science, with there being under representation of those who are not male and not white. Studies into broadening participation have looked at factors like student sense of belonging and self-efficacy. Much work in this area involves supporting college students in computing disciplines by attempting to improve college enrollment and undergraduate student retention. However, by the time students choose to major in CS, a large percentage of the population has already been lost. Girls' interest in CS dramatically decreases from primary to secondary school. Many students are driven away by negative stereotypes. One factor discouraging students from declaring a CS major is a lack of understanding and experience with CS. This disadvantage is especially prevalent for historically marginalized groups. Even among the common populace, a majority of students have no idea what computer scientists do. Some schools offer CS courses, but students with no experience are equally hesitant to take these courses. Increasing an understanding - and sparking an interest - in computer science would enable students to take CS courses in secondary school which would act as an on-ramp to a career in computing. Unplugged Learning Activities (UPAs) have been successful in raising student interest and self efficacy in CS. In this poster, we present an unplugged learning activity introducing students to the concept of reinforcement learning with and activity that has students build a physical model that ''learns'' to play 4x4 checkers by using candy.